<h2>What is FrauDB?</h2>
<p>Like mentioned on the homepage, FrauDB is a collaborative and cooperative database which collects and lists individuals engaged in both fraudulent and inconvenient/abusive activity on various web platforms.</p>
<p>As an example, if a customer of www.example.com buys a product from there but then uses that product for purposes against the provider's terms and conditions, then that provider can submit a listing request for that user by providing FrauDB with the proper context of why the user in question should be listed. Once that is approved, the <strong>personal details of the user are hashed</strong> and then entered into the database. <strong>This means that we never process or store any sensitive data</strong>, as all submitted data <strong>is hashed before it reaches our servers</strong>.</p>
<p>To learn more about how it works, visit the <a href="/how-it-works" class="link">How it works</a> page.</p>
<h2>Who can be a member?</h2>
<p>The great thing about this project is that it is a free and open source service, hosted with gracious contributions from various participating members. As such anyone can be a member, but memberships have to be applied for. If you'd like for your business/organisation to become a member, consider the following:</p>
<ul>
    <li>If you have a real-world use case for access to the database, e.g. have a website that requires background checking users, your application will likely be approved but on the grounds of your project's size.</li>
    <li>If you have data to contribute in exchange for the benefit you're receiving, your application is likely to be approved on the grounds of increasing the size of our database.</li>
</ul>
<p>These aren't requirements, but it helps to be able to show a real-world usecase for membership.</p>
