<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Can anyone submit a user report?</strong> &mdash; While user reports are usually made by members, anyone can indeed submit a report on a user if they have enough evidence of wrongdoing. Visit the <a href="https://users.fraudb.org/" class="link" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">user portal</a> to submit a standalone report.</li>
    <li><strong>If I've been listed, can I get de-listed</strong> &mdash; Everyone deserves a 2nd chance, including wrongdoers, if you believe you've been listed by accident, need to tell your side of a story or have simply been listed for long enough to have changed your ways, you may apply for a de-listing by visiting the <a href="https://users.fraudb.org/" class="link" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">user portal</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Does FrauDB cost anything?</strong> &mdash; No, we are a completely free and public service.</li>
    <li><strong>Who owns FrauDB?</strong> &mdash; FrauDB is owned by its members, this means every time a new member joins they get a say in how FrauDB is run and operates. We also have honorary membership for individuals and organisations who have contributed greatly to FrauDB.</li>
    <li><strong>Is my data in FrauDB?</strong> &mdash; As all data is hashed <em>before</em> it even reaches our APIs, your data is practically speaking not in FrauDB. This is because a hash is like a one-way ticket for data, it is completely impractical to reverse a SHA256 hash. To read more about this, visit the <a href="/how-it-works" class="link">How it works</a> page.</li>
</ul>